Now I have the file and the findings. Here's the refactor proposal, tied to each finding.

## Refactor proposal for `src/Card.tsx`

### 1. Accessible Interaction Risk (crime_00001) — line 10 `<div onClick>`

The outer wrapper handles a click but is rendered as a `<div>` with no `role`, `tabIndex`, or keyboard handler — keyboard and AT users can't reach it.

**Fix:** if the whole card is meant to be activatable, render it as a `<button type="button">` (or `<a href>` if it navigates). If only part of the card is interactive, lift the click to a real button inside and leave the card non-interactive.

```tsx
<button
  type="button"
  onClick={() => console.log("clicked")}
  className={styles.card}
>
  …
</button>
```

If the wrapper must stay a `<div>` for layout reasons, the minimum viable patch is `role="button"`, `tabIndex={0}`, and an `onKeyDown` handler that fires on `Enter`/`Space` — but a real `<button>` is preferred because it gets focus styles, activation semantics, and AT exposure for free.

### 2. Design Token Escape (crime_00002) — 9 raw style literals on lines 10/24

Hex/rgb/px values are inlined into `style={{…}}`, so the next agent editing the file has no signal that a token system exists.

**Fix:** move the styling out of `style` and into CSS (CSS Modules / Tailwind / styled-system — whichever the project uses) so values resolve from tokens:

```tsx
// Card.module.css
.card {
  background: var(--color-surface-accent);   /* was #ff00aa */
  color: var(--color-text-primary);          /* was #0a0a0a */
  border-color: var(--color-border-subtle);  /* was #cccccc */
  box-shadow: var(--shadow-sm);              /* was "0 2px 4px rgb(0,0,0)" */
  outline-color: var(--color-focus-ring);    /* was #1a73e8 */
  padding: var(--space-6);                   /* was 24 */
}
.body  { color: var(--color-text-primary); font-size: var(--text-md); }
.aside { color: var(--color-text-muted);   font-size: var(--text-sm); }
```

The point isn't to invent token names — it's that **none of these colors should be hex literals in JSX**. If no token system exists yet, this finding is the prompt to add one before the next agent copy-pastes `#ff00aa` into a sibling component.

### 3. Responsive Fragility (crime_00003) — fixed `width: 800` / `720`, no `@media`

Three fixed-px widths and a fixed font-size with no media query — the card overflows the viewport below ~820px.

**Fix:** swap fixed widths for fluid sizing and let the inner grid collapse:

```css
.card {
  width: 100%;
  max-width: 50rem;          /* was width: 800 */
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: minmax(0, 1fr) 15rem;  /* body + sidebar */
  gap: var(--space-4);
}
.body  { min-width: 0; font-size: clamp(1rem, 1vw + 0.75rem, 1.125rem); }
.aside { font-size: var(--text-sm); }

@media (max-width: 640px) {
  .card { grid-template-columns: 1fr; }   /* sidebar stacks under body */
  .aside { width: 100%; }
}
```

Key moves: `width: 100%` + `max-width` instead of fixed `800px`/`720px`, `clamp()` for the body font-size, and a single breakpoint that collapses the 2-column grid into one column on narrow viewports.

### Resulting component

```tsx
import styles from "./Card.module.css";

export function Card({
  children,
  onActivate,
}: {
  children: React.ReactNode;
  onActivate?: () => void;
}) {
  const Wrapper = onActivate ? "button" : "div";
  return (
    <Wrapper
      {...(onActivate && { type: "button", onClick: onActivate })}
      className={styles.card}
    >
      <div className={styles.body}>{children}</div>
      <aside className={styles.aside}>sidebar</aside>
    </Wrapper>
  );
}
```

Each change maps 1:1 to a finding: `<button>` clears `accessible_interaction_risk`, the CSS-module token references clear `design_token_escape`, and the fluid grid + `@media` query clears `responsive_fragility`.
